'''Jane Helen Ohlmeyer''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MRIA}} is a Northern Irish historian and academic, specialising in [[Early modern period|early modern]] [[History of Ireland|Irish]] and [[History of the British Isles|British history]]. Since 2003, she has been the [[Erasmus Smith's Professor of Modern History]] at [[Trinity College, Dublin]] (TCD). She has also served as Chair of the [[Irish Research Council]] since 2015. She was President of the [[Irish Historical Society]] from 2003 to 2005, and Vice-Provost for Global Relations at TCD from 2011 to 2014.<ref name="RIA">{{cite web|title=Jane Helen Ohlmeyer|url=https://www.ria.ie/jane-helen-ohlmeyer|website=[[Royal Irish Academy]]|accessdate=24 May 2018|date=19 October 2015}}</ref><ref name="Research">{{cite web|last1=Killard|first1=Fiona|title=Jane Ohlmeyer|url=https://www.tcd.ie/research/profiles/?profile=ohlmeyej|website=Trinity Research|publisher=Trinity College Dublin|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref><ref name="EHRI">{{cite web|title=Jane Ohlmeyer|url=https://www.ehri-project.eu/jane-ohlmeyer|website=European Holocaust Research Infrastructure|accessdate=24 May 2018|date=15 January 2015}}</ref><ref name="bio dept">{{cite web|title=Professor Jane Ohlmeyer|url=https://www.tcd.ie/history/staff/ohlmeyej.php|website=Department of History|publisher=Trinity College Dublin|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref><ref name="Queen">{{cite news|last1=Barrett|first1=David|title=Professor Jane Ohlmeyer: Queen of the Humanities|url=http://trinitynews.ie/professor-jane-ohlmeyer-queen-of-the-humanities/|accessdate=24 May 2018|work=[[Trinity News]]|date=2 November 2010}}</ref>

==Honours==
In 2011, Ohlmeyer was elected a [[Member of the Royal Irish Academy]] (MRIA), the premier all-Ireland [[learned society]] for the sciences and humanities.<ref name="RIA" />

