[[File:Takekoshi Yosaburo.jpg|thumb|right|Takekoshi Yosaburō]]
{{Japanese name|Takekoshi}}
{{Nihongo|'''Takekoshi Yosaburō'''|竹越 與三郎|extra=November 22, 1865 – January 12, 1950}} was a [[Japan]]ese historian and politician, member of the Diet and [[Privy Council (Japan)|Privy councillor]]. He was a graduate of [[Keio University|Keiō Gijuku]].

Takekoshi was a committed advocate of Japanese expansion into the South Seas, rather than China.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schencking|first1=J. Charles|title=The Imperial Japanese Navy and the Constructed Consciousness of a South Seas Destiny, 1872–1921|journal=Modern Asian Studies|date=October 1999|volume=33|issue=4|page=783|doi=10.1017/S0026749X99003649}}</ref>

Among his works published in English are ''Japanese Rule in Formosa''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Takekoshi|first1=Yosaburō|authorlink=Takekoshi Yosaburō|title=Japanese rule in Formosa|date=1907|publisher = Longmans, Green, and co.|publication-place = London, New York, Bombay and Calcutta|ol=6986981M|oclc=753129}}</ref> and a monumental ''Economic Aspects of the Civilization of Japan'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Takekoshi|first1=Yosaburō|title=Economic Aspects of the Civilization of Japan|date=1930|publisher=G. Allen & Unwin ltd.|location=London|ol=6742688M|oclc=6056613}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Takekoshi|first1=Yosaburo|title=The economic aspects of the history of the civilization of Japan|date=2003|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=0415323819|edition=[Reprint]}}</ref> which includes a wealth of quantitative data from pre-modern sources.

