{{DEFAULTSORT:Farfarers: Before the Norse, The}} [[Category:1998 books]] [[Category:Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact]] [[Category:Books by Farley Mowat]] [[Category:History of Orkney]] [[Category:Scandinavian Scotland]]

[[File:Tafel 1009 Bischof Thietmar v. Merseburg.jpg|thumb|240px|Thietmar of Merseburg in a [[Bas-relief]] by Karolin Donst, [[Tangermünde]]]]
'''Thietmar''' (also '''Dietmar''' or '''Dithmar'''; 25 July 975 – 1 December 1018), [[Bishopric of Merseburg|Prince-Bishop of Merseburg]] from 1009 until his death, was an important [[chronicler]] recording the reigns of [[King of the Romans|German kings]] and [[Holy Roman Emperor]]s of the [[Ottonian Dynasty|Ottonian]] ([[Duchy of Saxony|Saxon]]) dynasty.  Two of Thietmar's great-grandfathers, both referred to Liuthar, were the Saxon nobles [[Lothar II, Count of Stade]], and [[Lothar I, Count of Walbeck]].  They were both killed fighting the Slavs at the [[Battle of Lenzen]].

==Life==
[[File:Merseburgerdom.JPG|thumb|Merseburg Cathedral where Thietmar worked]]
Thietmar was a son of the Saxon count [[Siegfried I the Older, Count of Walbeck|Siegfried I the Older]] of [[Walbeck, Börde|Walbeck]] (d. 990) and his wife Kunigunde (d. 997), daughter of [[Henry I the Bald, Count of Stade|Henry I the Bald]], Count of [[Stade]] ([[Udonids|House of Udonids]]). His father fought with Margrave [[Odo I, Margrave of the Saxon Ostmark|Odo]] against Duke [[Mieszko I of Poland]] at the 972 [[Battle of Cedynia]]. At the time of Thietmar's birth, his family sided with the Ottonian duke [[Henry II, Duke of Bavaria|Henry II of Bavaria]] ("the Wrangler") in his uprising against his cousin Emperor [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto II]]. Later, a balance was achieved; Siegfried became [[burgrave]] at [[Möckern]] and his brother Count [[Lothair, Margrave of the Nordmark|Lothair of Walbeck]] served as [[margrave]] of the [[Northern March]] from 983 until his death in 1003.

Baptized in [[Bishopric of Halberstadt|Halberstadt]], Thietmar prepared for an ecclesiastical career. He was educated at the St. Servatius chapter of [[Quedlinburg Abbey]] and from 987 onwards at the [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictine]] abbey of Berge in [[Buckau (Magdeburg)|Buckau]] near [[Magdeburg]]. From 1 November 990, he attended the Magedeburg [[cathedral school]], together with his relative [[Bruno of Querfurt]]. He was familiar with the works of [[Augustine of Hippo]], but even more with classical authors like [[Virgil]], [[Horace]], [[Lucan]], and [[Macrobius]].

Thietmar witnessed the struggles of the young Ottonian king [[Otto III, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto III]] and his mother [[Theophanu]] to secure their reign. He took some part in some political events of the time; in 994 he was a hostage in the hands of the [[Norsemen]], and he was not unfamiliar with the actualities of war.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=849}} Upon the death of his parents, he inherited large parts of the Walbeck estates and in 1002 became [[Provost (religion)|provost]] of the family monastery, established by his grandfather Count Lothair II. On 21 December 1004, he was ordained as a priest by Archbishop [[Tagino|Tagino of Magdeburg]].

In 1009, through the intercession of Archbishop Tagino, he became Bishop of the Merseburg diocese, which had been re-established by King [[Henry II, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry II]] in 1004. Thietmar was concerned with the full restitution of his bishopric. A loyal supporter of the German kingship, he rarely interfered in political affairs. He died on 1 December 1018 and was buried in [[Merseburg cathedral]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=849}}

==Thietmar's Chronicle==
[[File:Page of Thietmars Chronicle.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Page of Thietmar's Chronicle]]
Between 1012 and 1018 Thietmar, while Bishop of Merseburg, composed his chronicle ''Chronicon Thietmari'', which comprises eight books,{{sfn|Ott|1909}} that cover the period between 908 and 1018, the Saxon Emperors [[Henry the Fowler]], the three Ottos, and [[Henry II the Saint]]. As counsellor of the Emperor and participant in many important political transactions he was well equipped for writing a history of his times.

The first three books, covering the reigns of Henry I and the first two Ottos ([[Otto I]] and [[Otto II]]) are largely based on previous chronicles most of which are still extant (e.g. [[Widukind of Corvey]]'s ''[[Res gestae Saxonicae]]'', the ''[[Annals of Quedlinburg|Annales Quedlinburgenses]]'' and others); the fourth book, comprising the reign of [[Otto III]] contains much original matter; while the remaining four books, which describe the reign of Henry II to the year 1018, are the independent narrative of Thietmar and, besides being the principal source for Saxon history during the reign of Henry II, contain valuable information, not to be found elsewhere regarding the contemporary history and civilization of the [[Polabian Slavs|Slavic tribes]] east of the [[river Elbe]], as well as [[Poles]], [[Hungarians]] and [[Bulgarians]].{sfn|Ott|1909}}

The [[Latin]] style and the composition are not of a high standard, largely because, as the original [[manuscript]] reveals, Thietmar continued to make amendments and insertions to the text after it was completed. Nor does he always discriminate between important and unimportant events.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}

The chronicle is nevertheless an excellent source for the history of [[Duchy of Saxony|Saxony]] during the reigns of the emperors Otto III and Henry II. No information is excluded by Thietmar, but the fullest details refer to the [[Bishopric of Merseburg]], and to the wars against the [[Wends]] (Polabian Slavs) and the Poles.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}

The original manuscript was moved in 1570 to [[Dresden]]. When the city was destroyed by [[Bombing of Dresden in World War II|bombing during World War II]] the manuscript was severely damaged, and only a few folios remain intact. Fortunately a complete [[facsimile]] edition had been published by L. Schmidt (Dresden, 1905).{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}

Thietmar's statement that the [[Gero Cross]] in [[Cologne cathedral]] was commissioned by [[Gero (Archbishop of Cologne)|Archbishop Gero]], who died in 976, was dismissed by art historians, who thought he meant another cross, until the 1920s, and finally confirmed as correct in 1976 by [[dendrochronology]].<ref name="Lauer">Lauer, Rolf. In Legner, Anton (ed). ''Ornamenta Ecclesiae, Kunst und Künstler der Romanik''., vol. III, 1985, p. 214</ref>

